=E2=80=99s publicist accidentally copying the reporter on a group chat =0Ac=
omplaining that Pierce didn=E2=80=99t pay them. (=E2=80=9CMs. Wesselman lau=
ghed off the =0Amessage, saying that the publicist was =E2=80=98totally mes=
sing with us.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D) There=E2=80=99s =0Athis:=0A=0AEven after a=
ll the setbacks, Mr. Pierce expresses a blithe confidence that he =0Acan be=
 a force for progress in Puerto Rico. But his self-assurance belies a =0Ape=
rsistent messiness in his business affairs. Among his friends, Mr. Pierce=
=E2=80=99s =0Aclash with Mr. Lipsey is the subject of vigorous armchair spe=
culation. Robert =0AAnderson, a crypto enthusiast who lives in Puerto Rico =
and is friendly with =0Aboth men, said they have behaved =E2=80=9Clike chil=
dren,=E2=80=9D acting out because they=E2=80=99re =0Abored. =E2=80=9CThey n=
eed some stimulation,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThey want to feel somethin=
g.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AI do think that a lot of crypto phenomena =E2=80=94 most l=
iterally Bored Apes =E2=80=94 have =0Athe form =E2=80=9Cearly crypto adopte=
