yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">discovered</a> that actually junk-rate=
d companies mostly generate enough cash to pay back their bonds, and that w=
as a pretty epochal discovery in the history of finance. =E2=80=9CIf a comp=
any has a steady-ish business with decent-ish cash flows, you can lend it m=
oney against those cash flows, if you charge a lot of interest=E2=80=9D add=
ed whole new dimensions to financial markets. There are not a ton of discov=
eries like that.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you can look elsewhere=
. One promising source of new discoveries is: You can invest in a company =
by=C2=A0<em>taking money=C2=A0</em>from someone else. If a company has rais=
ed $100 to run its business, and has promised the investors who put in that=
 $100 a reasonable rate of return, and then it loses money and wants to rai=
se more from you, it might not have anything left to promise you. Everythin=
g is already promised to the previous investors, and there=E2=80=99s not en=
ough money to pay everyone back, never mind to pay you too. And the solutio=
n is: You go to the company and say =E2=80=9Chere, I=E2=80=99ll lend you an=
other $20, but in return you have to stiff your previous investors and pay =
me back first.=E2=80=9D And then the company can somehow generate $120 of f=
inancing from only $100 (or less) of value. New financing has been created =
as if by magic. Not really. I mean, new financing has been created by takin=
g value from someone else who was already promised it.</p><p style=3D"margi=
